Errorf is a function from Go’s built-in fmt package.
It is used to create an error message, often with values inserted into it.
In your file
You see things like:
fmt.Errorf("get object %s: %w", key, err)
That means:
create an error
include the key
wrap the original err
Why f
The f means formatted.
Like:
Printf = print formatted
Sprintf = string formatted
Errorf = error formatted
What it returns
It returns an error.
So fmt.Errorf(...) creates a new error value.
Why we use it
Because it lets us:
add context
include variable values
preserve the original error sometimes
Example
fmt.Errorf("read object %s: %w", key, err)
means:
something failed while reading object key
include the original error too
Very short version
Errorf = create a formatted error message
comes from fmt
returns an error
